        "what_text": "\"The Ambassadors programme started around 2018. Discussions around every day leadership and the meaning of leadership roles led the school to make a bold change: the removal of captain roles, replaced by \"\"ambassador\"\" roles. Over time these roles have matched into the work of departments and areas of the school. The roles have evolved to meet the needs of young people in the school with ambassadors focus on support for learning, wellbeing, extra-curricular opportunities, transition, digital skills, and many other areas of practice.\n\n\n\nThe work of Ambassador development started when a small group of pupils attended East Dunbartonshire Council training on Augmented and Alternative Communication. The effect on the young people was profound - one young person changed their UCAS application in order to focus on Educational Psychology rather than their original Science-based pathway. Two of the team had applied for captaincy roles and had been unsuccessful - an indication, perhaps, that the system wasn't reflecting the value of the work.\n\n\n\nOver the following years, pupils and staff identified roles, invented new roles, and were awarded badges to recognise their place in the leadership of the schools. Ambassadors have contributed to the school in a multitude of ways, including:\n\n\n\n- Event planning and organising - discos, proms, charity events.\n\n- Supporting young people in class on a one to one and whole class level\n\n- Visiting and working with young people in primary school through digital learning, sports, reading and languages\n\n- Supporting wellbeing through wellbeing focused clubs, and highlighting positive mental health strategies through assemblies\n\n- Led the development of a charities committee that reflects the views and supportive actions of the community \n\n- Represented the school at events and organised teams to support young people at events\n\n- Run extra curricular opportunities including sports coaching, science and engineering clubs\n\n- Supported staff and pupils as digital ambassadors with online homework tools and Glow, including supporting parents\n\n- Supporting the school library\n\n- Supporting language development in class and with individual pupils\n\n- Supporting Young Enterprise competitions and events in school\n\n\n\nA particular achievement has been the impactful work of peer mentor support in Mathematics and Chemistry, where young people support students in the years below to study - in the form of classroom support and interventions.\"",
