        "hgios_score": 6,
        "tags": [],
        "what_text": "Cohorts of learners at Bearsden Academy have consistently outstanding levels of attainment from S1 to S3 and in National Qualifications, with young people achieving much better across all comparator measures than learners with similar needs and backgrounds across Scotland – this is made clear in Insight data, using the Virtual Comparator, Local Authority and National Benchmarks.\n\nThis is supported by sustained and outstanding levels of literacy and numeracy in S3 and in the Senior Phase, with almost all pupils reaching L4 Literacy and Numeracy.\n\nThere is very strong attainment across the Senior Phase. In S4, National 5 results are ahead of comparators when looking at success in 5 or more N5s, and within the majority of departments. In 2024, half of subjects in S4 were significantly ahead of their course comparator in Insight and most subjects have positive results for most years in the last 5 years.\n\nNational 5 and Higher results have continually improved over the last three years and have sustained, high levels of A passes and overall pass rates. Presentation rates are consistently higher in major subjects such as English and Maths than other schools in the Local Authority. Where schools are meeting with a similar level of results, Bearsden Academy adds more “value added” versus the Virtual Comparator than similar schools.\n\nA significant percentage of pupils – 50% of S4 roll in 2025 – achieve at least one Advanced Higher, peaking in 2023 with 54%. \n\nInsight data shows that leavers and S4-S6 cohorts achieve above Virtual Comparators, Local Authority and National measures over time, particularly when looking at complementary tariff points, due to the high uptake of SQA qualifications for young people.\n\nSenior leaders in the school are able to analyse the results each year to find clear strengths and areas for development, producing detailed breakdowns for the local authority, and finding ways to group small cohort data (e.g. SIMD Q1) in order the draw conclusions.\n\nAn example of this analysis is the demonstration that over 5 years, average points for SIMD Q1 pupils is 112 points lower than Q5 pupils over that time – which is the lowest gap in the Local Authority. Also, in each year group, the lowest 20% of attainment has increased over time.\n\nAt department level, every Principal Teacher generates a report based on their own priorities, identifying areas of strength and development for their subjects. These are used to get an overall view of attainment and how it is achieved: importantly, all staff are involved in the meetings around attainment.\n\nInterventions over a session come via Guidance referrals, tracking meetings and an intervention programme. The collective effort of staff allows many pupils who were off track to gain a pass – a majority of those identified as borderline or failing post-prelim go on to pass at National 5 and Higher.\n\nThe drive for attainment requires autonomy for departments – this can be seen by the variety of interventions offered by teachers over a session – many of which sit outside of structures provided by Study Support.",
