        "what_now_steps": "- Data-Driven Intervention: The SDS Meta-skills Profiling and subsequent tracking data must be used to target intervention and tailor curriculum delivery precisely where meta-skills gaps are identified (e.g., if data reveals a weakness in 'Adaptability' in S3, the curriculum should respond)\n\n- Systemic Moderation: The three whole-school Moderation Events annually will be used not just for quality assurance, but to generate clear, actionable CLPL and support strategies that rapidly raise the standard of skills teaching across all departments.\n\n- Formalising Experiential Learning: Authentic initiatives like the S6 Cafe Initiative and the 'Find Your Inspiration' Programme must be used to formally assess and record meta-skills acquisition, creating tangible evidence (case studies, portfolios) that pupils can use confidently in future applications and interviews.\n\n- Embedding Innovation: The creative curriculum examples in PE and English need to be systematically shared and replicated across other departments. This ensures the flexibility gained from staffing changes is used to continually evolve teaching methodologies and course offerings, maintaining curricular agility.\n\n- SLT-Driven Review: The annual August SLT curriculum planning meeting will be essential for reviewing the outcomes of the previous year's Moderation and KPI reporting and using this evidence to formally set the strategic goals for the next Curriculum Improvement Cycle (CIC).\n\nPupil Voice for Future Planning: Feedback from the Pupil Voice Improvement Team will be structurally integrated into the 'Plan' phase of the CIC, ensuring that future curriculum development is driven by the authentic needs and experiences of the learners themselves."
