        "tags": [],
        "what_text": "Learners in today’s society require digital skills to succeed – digital skills are noteable in 21st century skills frameworks, highlighted in terms of employability as well as personal safety and cybersecurity.\n\nBearsden Academy has focused on digital tools for learning, primarily outside of the classroom. The use of devices within school has expanded, with use of iPads across a range of departments, as well as the use of computers in subjects where they are available. Computer suites can also be accessed by any class through a booking.\n\nDigital tools have supported learning universally through supporting access to homework and learning outside of school. Digital assessment tools are used to support Senior Phase pupils and digital tools support the learning needs of young people in class and during assessments. Teachers also benefit from using digital tools to improve learning and teaching, and data analysis.\n\n## Digital Technology in class\n\n- Pupils learn digital skills such as graphic creation, presentation and document creation via S1/S2 Computing Science and S2 Business. \n\n- Pupils use iPads in classes such as English, French and PSE. In French, pupils use this technology to access audio and video for language development. \n\n- All pupils access computers in PSE to support access to My World of Work, and to supporting college and university applications. \n\n- In PE, pupils use iPads to record techniques and review their performances\n\n- Teachers use interactive white board presentations to allow learners to contribute on the board\n\n- Visualisers are used to share writing and experiments\n\n## Digital technology to support learning at home\n\n- Pupils all have access to Glow, and this is used to communicate with pupils\n\n- Teams is used by most departments to share files, updates and assignments. In English, Teams is used as the central tool to track and provide assessment. \n\n- Achieve is used to provide exam preparation resources including quizzes, self evaluation checklists and past paper questions\n\n- The school has begun developing a family learning digital resource, which is focused on discussion and sharing of learning at home\n\n- All pupils and parents have access to Satchel One, which allows tracking of homework – this is used as a focused tool for learners that struggle to organise for homework\n\n## Digital tools for assessment\n\n- Within assessment, digital tools are used for delivery and to aid the completion of assessment\n\n- Learning tools such as the immersive reader tools within MS Word, reading and speech-to-text tools are all used to support learners. Colour changing digital overlays and read aloud tools aid pupils in accessing text during assessment.\n\n## Improving learning and teaching with digital tools\n\n- Staff use digital quiz tools to provide an engaging experience for retrieval practice and formative assessment, including Gymkit, Wayground and Kahoot\n\n- Activote is used to sample pupil feedback, particularly in Science classes\n\n- Teachers have been learning to use AI tools to create and enhance resources – in 2025, Modern Studies has been focused on a practitioner enquiry on AI.\n\nWe have continued to build on our cluster award for Digital Schools in 2019. We have regularly engaged with primary schools around digital learning using digital ambassadors to support learning in primary – in 2025, Advanced Higher pupils have been teaching primary pupils in Balljaffray using coding with Scratch.",
