        "hgios_score": 5,
        "tags": [],
        "what_text": "Bearsden Academy has history of working groups and improvement teams, and the Learning and Teaching toolkit that is currently used in the school is an example of a staff-led, working group-focused change to practice. In 2020, the model of meeting and developing improvement priorities was difficult to continue with as the school moved to a recovery plan for 2020-2021. Following this, the Senior Leadership Team consulted with staff over a variety of exercises to gauge opinions of moving forward with improvement and leading on improvement. This involved mapping time into the Working Time Agreement to support meeting time, and providing a structure for improvement. \n\n[pdf: BA Improvement Team Book.pdf]\n\nThe tools for improvement have evolved over time, and have looked at cycles of improvement, focus on equity and impact, and setting realistic targets. Evidence shows use of improvement cycle methodologies in 2022, 2023 and 2024, using teams of teaching staff to develop and plan actions based on priorities in the improvement plan.Through the leadership shown across many groups, the school has managed to link staff improvement teams to pupil improvement teams, with leads liaising between the two groups. This has allowed pupils to negotiate the direction of travel, advise, and provide their own ideas for improvement, whilst also understanding how school priorities may be have a wider focus.\n\nThe management of the groups has been responsive: where time has not been available to meet due to other pressures, we have adjusted planning. In the 2025 session, we focused on making action plans per improvement priority. This meant groupings changed, but were focused strongly on the work to generate improvement versus the plan. \n\nThe school also uses PEF to create temporary leadership roles to support elements of improvement – this has included, over time, Wider Achievement, STEM Nation, Digital Learning, Creativity and Outdoor Learning.",
