        "what_text": "Young people at Bearsden Academy have regular opportunities to engage in pupil leadership. \n\nThe Ambassador programme allows senior pupils to support young pupils in departments across the school. Pupil leaders help younger pupils in a variety of approaches including mentoring, paired reading, and wellbeing support. The majority of S6 pupils lead through Ambassador roles, supporting extra-curricular and learning opportunities. Ambassador roles also allow young people to be involved in wider school events; for example, The Language and Culture Event and Charity events.  As a result, young people engage collaboratively with key partners within our school community. \n\nThe Leadership Curriculum roadmap highlights the accredited leadership opportunities available to young people in the curriculum. The Pupil Leadership working group created the map to demonstrate recognised qualifications and skills. \n\nThe Pupil Improvement Team was established in the school in 2024. Over fifty young people from S1-S6 volunteered to take part in this leadership opportunity.  The annual cycle highlights the opportunities young people have throughout the year to be actively involved in decision making processes.  Young people elect to be part of an ‘Improvement Team’ group and work alongside a staff link. \n\nYoung people engage with ‘How Good is OUR School?’ Statements and discuss strengths and next steps for L & T with their peers. They present their findings at year group assemblies, and all young people can provide further feedback through a Form on Satchel One/by joining the team. Young people meet with staff links to create action plans which are then shared at a Business Breakfast with parents/carers and other school community partners. The self-evaluative work from The Pupil Improvement team informs school improvement priorities. ‘You said, we did’ assemblies take place at the end of the school year. \n\nBuilding on previous Pupil Council initiatives, The Pupil Parliament was established in August 2025.  Young people voted in registration for their chosen representative (s).  Young people in the Pupil Parliament met to explore HGIOURS theme 4 statements to be voted on in registration. In registration, young people voted on their chosen statement which will inform health and wellbeing planning. A ‘You said, we did’ assembly led by young people will take place at the end of the year.\n\n\n\n",
